Title: Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
The director did such a formulaic job of timing and foreshadowing what was going to happen that my kid and I were predicting and quoting lines of dialog before they were spoken by the characters.  The predictability and formulas were not too detracting, as usual, you just waited for the kicker line, and then the  action sequence, and go "yeah called it!"   Like any good rollercoaster, you see the hill coming before you plummet, and that makes it fun.  

Story-wise, yeah, totally different from the novel, but improved, in my opinion.  Certain things like character allegiances and motivations that Dashner left frustatingly hazy were made pointedly clear in the screenplay, the effect for me being one of relief rather than ire.

Comment:
I remember having my doubts on reading the books because of all the bad reviews it got. But once I started, I couldn't stop. And then I heard they were going to adapt it into a movie, and I just had to see it. I had doubts then too, because before anything else, I'm an avid reader. But they did an amazing job with the first movie, and it looks like they did an amazing job for this one, and I can't wait to see it. My point?

As¬†an avid reader, I understand why people want the movies to be at least 95% like the books. But also speaking as a film fanatic, I also know movie adaptations are never going to be exactly like the books. But as long as they've kept the general storyline/setting/characters the same, I'm not too fussed (unless they majorly change something). What I'm trying to say is, book readers, don't judge a movie until you've actually seen it (open mind and all that), and film fanatics, know that you may not understand something unless you've read the books, so either do that or research on the stuff you don't understand.

Comment:
This looks like a solid movie. The first one had some weak moments, but was a surprisingly good movie. This one looks like it has an even stronger storyline, and this trailer has set my expectations pretty high.¬†
And to everyone saying "The book is wayyyy better," let me ask you. Have you EVER said "the movie is wayyyy better than the book"? Probably not. Because you can't really compare them. A book and a movie are two very, VERY different things. They are completely different forms of entertainment. You simply cannot include every single detail of a book in a movie. That's why it's called an adaptation, it's clearly the same story but with some changes. What works on a page does not always work well on the screen. The author has said over and over again that he is perfectly fine with the changes, and he's even said that they make more sense.¬†
So please, understand that basically all book-to-movie adaptations have changes made to them. You should expect that by now, seriously. Stop expecting them to be the same, and then you won't be disappointed.¬†
I have understood for a long time that books and movies simply can't really be compared, you have to go into them realizing that they are two different things. I've read this entire series, and I'm fine with the changes to the movies. They work on the big screen. This movie looks really, really good and I can't wait to see it, no matter how many changes they made.

Title: Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I'm very happy that they made enormous amendments to the original book. Where the original Maze Runner book was somewhat interesting and compelling, every book after were lacking in originality and conceptuality ( Not detracting that the original premise and the whole idea has very little appeal by the time you figure out the whole story in the 3rd book).

The Scorch Trial book when it came down to it was a glorified zombie thriller that did little to advance the plot and largely had very few interesting parts. Them choosing to change it enormously may help even out some issues that the second book lacked and might better position the cast in a more interesting vantage point for the third book.

Title: Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Looks to me as they combined book two and three. Wich I think is okay. The story as it's told in the books is very difficult to convey to screen. There was a lot of mystery and confusion. Wih is fine if you know there is a third book that explains everything, but not if you're watching a movie. In a movie, a little mystery is captivating and keeps you watching, too much and it gets too confusing to follow.

The book heavily depended on Thomas's thoughts and interpretations of things, flashbacks and telekenisis. It is very hard, if not impossible, to convey that to a movie without being clich√©.

I think they have made some difficult choices regarding the book plot, but I think it was neccesary to do the story justice.

There is so many changes, just looking at the trailer.¬†

I mean, in the book, they get put into the scorch, rather then escape to it.
Also, did anyone else imagine the little place they were put into -in the start of the book- was small? It made the place seem very small, the way they walked around and they could only see a few doors.

And, when they see all the other people presumably from the other glade, it makes no sense! I mean, there is like a mixture of females and males there, when in the book there was only like 1 boy which was Aris and another group of girls which they do not meet until they venture out into the actual scorch.

It is all so different, it is scary.

Some parts you can see relate to the story, like in the trailer, when Brenda fell I think it relates to when the tower was falling down.¬†

But, I don't think that in the book we see Teresa boarding the "ship" with Avia etc.

It does look like a good movie, but hopefully we will see some more trailers soon and it might explain it better.

Really looking forward to it!

I was fine with most of the changes in the first movie, because that book had a lot of elements that just wouldn't work in a film. Scorch, however, is a very simple, straight-up survival thriller that would *not* be very hard to translate to the screen. Maybe I'm being picky, (after all, it's just one trailer) but I really loved this book, and I don't want to see it ruined. All that said, I'm still  #ReadyForScorch !

I trust Dashner's judgment, so I'll accept the changes that have been made. When I first watched it, I had no idea what to make of it. Regardless, I'm super excited to see it!
